post_text:
Rocky Mountain School would like to recognize Cherokee Nation as they continue to provide strong partnerships with area schools. Today, our school received $10,000 as part of their Covid-19 Respond, Recover and Rebuild spending plan. These monies are being utilized to purchase technology devises for students, as well as, additional PPE supplies for the district.
We are blessed to be a recipient of these funds and value Cherokee Nation’s continued support of our school. Thank you!

shared_text:
Cherokee Nation
July 13 at 6:18 PM ·

Cherokee Nation recently launched an online application for our Respond, Recover and Rebuild Education Initiative. Thousands of families have already applied for these student grants, which will help
ease the impact of COVID-19 on their pursuit of education. But, we need everyone to apply by the August 7 deadline. You can find the application online at www.cherokee.org; just look for the blue Respond, Recover and Rebuild Education Initiative link on the front page. You'll also find an important FAQ at the very top of the Cherokee Nation's website to help answer some of your most frequent questions. If you still have questions, feel free to call our education initiative call center during normal business hours at (918) 453-5088.

Cherokee Nation Principal Chief Chuck Hoskin Jr. and Cherokee Nation Deputy Principal Chief Bryan Warner answer a few of those important questions in this video, so take a look:

Activities for Monday, April 20th, 10:00-noon
🚀 2nd and 5th-8th grade Learning Packet Pick Up for the last 3 weeks of school
🚀 5th-8th athletes may pick up belongings from lockers. Items will be outside of gym. Stay in your car. Staff will assist you.

🚀 Remember our campus is closed to the public. If the times listed conflict with your schedule do to your work, please call or text me to make other arrangements.
😊 Have a great rest of the weekend. Stay safe and stay healthy.

post_text:
Beginning April 13th, we will be distributing weekly meals on Mondays only from 10:00 AM - 12:00 PM. At that time, you may pick up 5 breakfast and 5 lunches for each child in the household that is 18 and under. We feel this will benefit our families with time, mileage and exposure.

Items will be packed so that some assembly may be required. E.g. meat, cheese, and bread will be packaged separately in order to maintain optimum freshness during the week.
Parents or designated persons are now able to pick up meals and children do not have to be present.

This program is for ALL children 18 and under. This works the same as the daily school lunch program. It is not an issue of whether you have enough food in your house or not. You taking a meal, does not take away from another child. This is a program to HELP each of our families.

If you want to order meals for your children, fill out one survey per household. This will assist us in ordering and preparing an adequate amount of meals. Thank you!

post_text:
Distance Learning Day 1........
Packet pickup went great!

Shoutout to all parents and students who brought smiles, encouraging words, and air hugs as you came through the line! You are the best!!!

Remember, this is not the way any of us expected to complete the year. Don’t stress over the transition. We are all learning this together. Parents, keep reassuring and encouraging your children. Unconditional love, support, and kindness to others are some of the best lessons they can learn. Not all important lessons are taught through textbooks and the within the walls of a school.

Rocky Mountain teachers and staff have poured thought, love and prayers into your packets. I know you appreciate them as much as I do. Teachers will be contacting families from time to time. If you have any questions, please reach out to them or me. We are here for you and happy to help.

PS - I suppose all went well today with student behavior. I had zero distress calls needing to send anyone to the superintendent’s office. 😊
Have a great week! 💙

Monday, April 6, 2020

All students, PreK 3’s - 8th grade, have a packet that needs to be picked up. Students do not have to be present. If parents are working, send an older sibling or other designated adult to pick up your child’s things.

Last Name
A-H, 9:00-10:30
I-P, 10:30-12:00
Q-Z, 12:00-1:30

It is our hope that Monday runs as smoothly as possible. However, we certainly hope and appreciate you arriving armored with patience, understanding and grace as we work through this process.

We love and appreciate each of you and are looking forward to seeing you on Monday.
Please stay safe and healthy.

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 25 at 2:51 PM ·

The State Board of Education unanimously approved an order that implements a Distance Learning Plan to complete the 2019-20 school year for Oklahoma students without reopening school buildings.

While education will resume on April 6 with distance learning, there will not be traditional, in-person instruction or extracurricular activities. Districts will be expected to follow critical safety guidance from the Centers for Disease Control with regard to social distancing for students, staff and school families.

“Oklahoma has tremendous educators – strong, dedicated, tenacious and smart. We have faith and confidence that our districts and teachers are committed to creative and innovative ways to continue learning for their students, and they will rise to this challenge." - State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

Read more about today's board action here:

State Superintendent of Public Instruction Joy Hofmeister announced today that she will propose a Continuous Learning Plan to the State Board of Education this week to complete the school year for Oklahoma students without reopening school buildings during the global pandemic. While the education of schoolchildren will resume with distance learning, there will not be traditional, in-person instruction or extracurricular activities, instead following critical safety guidance from the Centers for Disease Control with regard to social distancing for students, staff and school families.

The Board will hold a special meeting on Wednesday, March 25. Board members will meet virtually

March 16, 2020

RMS staff and parents,
As many of you are aware, State Superintendent Hofmeister called an emergency board meeting this afternoon of the state board of education. The state board just voted to cease school and school activities for all public schools in the state of Oklahoma until April 6th.
In the next few days, I will be giving you additional information concerning such items as meals for students, community supports, and guidance on continuing your child’s learning during this time.
I appreciate the continued support of Rocky Mountain school. We are blessed with a wonderful community.
If you have any questions or concerns, you may reach out to me personally by texting or calling my cell phone, 918-797-0318.
May God bless each of us during this time.

post_text: Congratulations to the Rocky Mountain Robotics team!!! These kids have worked diligently through the year to design, build, tear apart, rebuild, and adjust their projects in order to compete at various meets on Saturdays. Today, the 5th and 6th grade teams competed in the State Robotics Meet. Each team member has specific jobs/tasks in order for their team to compete successfully. These teams competed, watched and learned from other teams, made many new friends, and great memories. Sixth grade advanced through to the finals today. Many thanks to Mr. Preston Hudson for sponsoring this program and challenging our students to reach their highest potential at each competition. Looking forward to watching this program grow and develop at Rocky Mountain!

Students and Staff alike seemed to enjoy the first day of 2019-20!!!
Today, we talked about being “Smarties” for this school year. We will all use our brains in order to increase our knowledge and become “smarter” than we were the year before. We will make “smart” choices concerning our words and actions and strive to spread kindness to those around us. We will also be “smart” by showing respect to our elders each other. There are so many ways in life to display our “smarts” to others.
So thankful and blessed to work each day with a awesome group of “SMARTIES!”

post_text:
Cherokee Nation Remember the Removal Bike Riders will stop and spend the night at Rocky Mountain School on Wednesday, June 19th. They are expected to arrive at school at approximately 4:00 PM. We would like to invite the community to come Wednesday and help extend a “welcome home” to the riders prior to their homecoming in Tahlequah the following morning.

Once they are finished, they will have logged approx 950 miles that the ancestors traveled during The Trail of Tears. This year marks the 35th Anniversary of the Remember the Removal Bike Ride. Rocky Mountain’s own Marie Eubanks is participating this year as one of the mentor riders. She has ridden a strong ride and is looking forward to sharing her experience and knowledge of history with others.

Make plans Wednesday to be at the school early to welcome the riders and plan to stay a while for a casual afternoon to visit, take pictures, learn what it takes to participate on future rides and show encouragement to the riders.

post_text:
Sunday, May 26
Washington DC, 1 of 3
Today, we visited several Smithsonian Institute Museums - The Castle, Air and Space, American Indian, Natural History, and American History.
We witnessed the final drive of the Rolling Thunder - hundreds of thousands of motorcycles drive through DC to bring awareness for POW and MIA and veterans who have not received fair treatment.
We got lunch from the food trucks and enjoyed eating on the lawn of the National Mall.
We visited the Washington Memorial, the Holocaust Museum, Air Force Memorial And 911 Memorial.

Great job Rockets and Lady Rockets!! Our 6/7 grade teams played tonight against two great teams in our area.

Our boys played hard, they placed 4th against Briggs in the Stilwell 7th grade tournament! (I didn’t get a picture!)

The girls played Woodall. They played with all their heart and soul! They may have not won on the scoreboard, but these girls won our hearts with drive and determination up to the last second of the game! (Photo credit to Mrs. Brown)

This will be an exciting year in basketball!
